! instantiated-by: Prototype 10 — Wiring Diagram LLM [🔸/小 🐲/乃]
  :maturity :design
  :depends-on [f6/P0, f6/P7]
  :evidence-for-active [Metatheory v3.0 defines 78-type schema; CT validation baseline; local topology metrics operational]

  + context: The wiring diagram metatheory (v3.0) defines mathematical text as a
    colored operad with 30 component types, 11 port types, 5 wire types, and 32
    wire labels. Classical regex detection finds components and wires individually
    but cannot wire endpoints (50% orphan rate). LLM extraction fills this gap
    but is expensive at scale. Training a dedicated model enables batch processing.

  + IF: You want to extract wiring diagrams from all of math.SE (~500K-1.5M QA pairs)
  + HOWEVER: API-based LLM extraction is too expensive at that scale
  + THEN: Train a dedicated wiring diagram LLM on the superpod using distillation
    from Claude labels, with math.SE as bulk training data
  + BECAUSE: The task decomposes into two learnable functions that LLMs natively
    understand: text→wiring (extraction) and wiring→wiring (Q→A reasoning)

  + ARCHITECTURE:

    Task 1 — Text → Wiring Diagram (extraction):
      Input: mathematical text (SE answer, PM definition, nLab article)
      Output: {components: [...], ports: [...], wires: [...]} (78-type JSON)
      Training: distill from Claude on seed labels → fine-tune on bulk

    Task 2 — Wiring Diagram → Wiring Diagram (reasoning):
      Input: question wiring diagram (open ports, missing conclusion)
      Output: answer wiring diagram (filled ports, added wires, conclusion)
      Training: every math.SE Q→A pair provides one (Q_wiring, A_wiring) example
      Insight: Q→A is native to LLM pretraining; wiring diagrams make the
        reasoning structure explicit rather than implicit in surface text

    Validation loop:
      answer_wd = Task2(question_wd)
      answer_text = render(answer_wd)
      recovered_wd = Task1(answer_text)
      assert similar(answer_wd, recovered_wd)  # round-trip consistency

    Quality signal (free, no human labels):
      Local topology metrics as reward model —
        orphan rate, sink property, reachability, CAR/arity match
      The classical baseline provides negative examples (high orphan rate)
      Claude-labeled provides positive examples (well-formed wiring)

  + DATA INVENTORY:
    data[PlanetMath: 9,451 entries — gold standard definitions with CAR, arity, pmrelated graph]
    data[nLab: ~20,000 articles — cross-referenced, 137 bridge concepts to PM CT]
    data[Math.SE: ~500K-1.5M QA pairs — bulk reasoning data, native Q→A structure]
    data[Physics.SE: 114K QA pairs — already processed, cross-domain validation]
    data[NER kernel: 19,236 terms — domain vocabulary for typed slots]
    data[Golden-20 CT entries: pre-baked wiring prompts for seed labeling]

  + TRAINING PIPELINE:
    stage[1. Seed: Claude labels 200 entries with full wiring JSON (golden + bridge concepts)]
    stage[2. Bootstrap: LoRA fine-tune Llama-3-8B on seed labels for Task 1]
    stage[3. Scale: Run bootstrap model on math.SE via superpod (new Stage 3b)]
    stage[4. Filter: Keep extractions with low orphan rate + correct sink property]
    stage[5. Train: Full fine-tune on filtered math.SE wiring pairs for Task 1 + Task 2]
    stage[6. Validate: Check against PM gold standard — CAR match, arity match, topology improvement]
    stage[7. Curriculum: Use in-link stratification for curriculum learning — train on foundational concepts first]

  + EVIDENCE:
    evidence[Wiring diagram metatheory v3.0: 78 types (30 component + 11 port + 5 wire + 32 label)]
    evidence[CT validation: 313 PM entries, classical baseline (3.93 comp/entry, 3.60 wire/entry)]
    evidence[Local topology: 21% well-formed by classical (50% orphan rate = the gap LLM fills)]
    evidence[PM↔nLab bridge: 137 concept pairs for cross-corpus validation]
    evidence[PM in-link stratification: 9,451 entries, 18,326 links, power-law distribution]
    evidence[Component:wire ratio encodes style: PM 2:1 (reference) vs nLab 1:3 (tutorial)]
    evidence[Rewiring morphism: structured transformation preserving content, changing pedagogy]
    evidence[Colored operad structure: meta/domain/informal sorts with typed port constraints]
    evidence[Quotient functor tower: curriculum = sequence of coarsenings over the operad]
    evidence[Technote: technote-colored-operad-curriculum.md]

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[Download math.SE dump and estimate actual corpus size]
    next[Generate 200 Claude-labeled wiring diagrams from golden + bridge entries]
    next[Build LoRA training script for Task 1 (text → wiring JSON)]
    next[Design wiring diagram serialization format for Task 2 (compact, tokenizer-friendly)]
    next[Add Stage 3b to superpod-job.py: wiring extraction via fine-tuned model]
    next[Build Blockly prototype for visualization of extracted wiring diagrams]

  :success-criteria
    pass[Task 1 extracts wiring diagrams with <20% orphan rate on PM gold standard]
    pass[Task 2 generates answer wirings that round-trip through Task 1]
    pass[Model runs on superpod at >100 entries/minute]
    pass[Extracted wirings match classical baseline on component/wire counts (±20%)]
    fail[Model hallucinates component types not in the 78-type schema]
    fail[Orphan rate worse than classical baseline (>50%)]

  :psr-example "Selected wiring diagram LLM because API extraction doesn't scale to math.SE"
  :pur-template "Training run {{id}}, task: {{T1|T2}}, data: {{count}}, orphan_rate: {{rate}}"


! instantiated-by: Prototype 11 — Structural Hypergraph Embeddings (LWGM) [🔸/小 🐲/乃]
  :maturity :design
  :depends-on [f6/P7, f6/P10]
  :evidence-for-active [NNexus Glasses demo validates all annotation layers on thread #633512; s-exp surface parsing curated]

  + context: The pipeline produces rich per-thread annotations — NER terms, scope
    bindings, wiring edges, categorical detections, expression surfaces — but these
    remain local to each thread. There is no global structure connecting threads by
    the *shape* of their mathematical arguments. Text embeddings (Stage 2) capture
    lexical similarity but not structural similarity: two threads using different
    words for the same pattern of reasoning land far apart.

  + IF: You want "related questions" to mean "structurally analogous reasoning"
    (e.g. a thread about sheaf cohomology and one about group extensions share the
    same universal-property + Let-binding + diagram-chase shape)
  + HOWEVER: Text embeddings encode surface form, not argument structure
  + THEN: Assemble a typed hypergraph per thread from all annotation layers, then
    embed hypergraphs into a vector space using graph neural networks; index for
    structural similarity search
  + BECAUSE: The annotation layers already decompose mathematical arguments into
    typed components — the hypergraph makes this structure explicit and the
    embedding makes it searchable

  + ARCHITECTURE:

    Stage 8 — Expression Surface Parsing (CPU x128):
      Input: thread wiring JSON + raw LaTeX from body_html
      Output: s-exp parse tree per expression, typed by scope context
      Method: deterministic LaTeX parser (recursive descent, ~150 LOC Python)
      Evidence: curated s-exp parses for 30 expressions in thread #633512

    Stage 9a — Thread Hypergraph Assembly (CPU):
      Input: NER terms + scope bindings + wiring edges + categorical labels + s-exp surfaces
      Output: one typed hypergraph per thread, format: {nodes: [...], hyperedges: [...], types: [...]}
      Node types: expression-surface, ner-term, scope-binding, post
      Hyperedge types: wiring-edge (assert/clarify/challenge/...),
        scope-binds (which scope governs which expressions),
        categorical-span (which cat concept covers which subgraph),
        term-occurrence (which NER term appears in which expression surface)
      The hypergraph is the thread's *structural signature*.

    Stage 9b — Hypergraph Embedding (GPU):
      Input: typed hypergraphs (batch of ~2M threads)
      Output: fixed-dimensional embedding vector per thread (e.g. d=768)
      Model candidates:
        - Graphormer (Microsoft): graph transformer, handles typed edges
        - GPS (General Powerful Scalable): hybrid message-passing + transformer
        - HGNN+ (Hypergraph Neural Networks): native hyperedge support
        - HyperSAGE: inductive, handles unseen node types
      Training signal (free, no human labels):
        - Contrastive: threads sharing tags should embed nearby
        - Contrastive: threads linked by SE "related questions" should embed nearby
        - Contrastive: threads firing same categorical detections should embed nearby
        - Negative: random thread pairs from different tag clusters
      Could also distill: use Claude to judge structural similarity on 1K pairs
        as gold supervision, then train the GNN to match.

    Stage 10 — Structural Similarity Index (CPU):
      Input: embedding vectors for all threads
      Output: FAISS index + k-NN similarity graph
      Enables: "find me threads with the same argument shape as this one"
      The similarity graph itself becomes a new annotation layer:
        structural neighbours are candidates for cross-domain pattern discovery (P2)

  + THE LWGM VISION:
    A Large Wiring Graph Model is not an LLM — it embeds *argument structure*,
    not token sequences. The embedding space has dimensions corresponding to
    mathematical reasoning patterns, not word frequencies. Querying it asks
    "what other threads reason like this one?" — a question no text-based
    retrieval system can answer well.

    Downstream uses:
    - Structural search: find threads by argument shape, not keywords
    - Pattern discovery: clusters in embedding space = recurring reasoning patterns
    - Curriculum generation: path through embedding space = learning trajectory
    - Anomaly detection: threads far from all clusters = novel reasoning
    - Cross-domain transfer: "this algebra thread has the same shape as that topology thread"

  + DATA REQUIREMENTS:
    data[Thread wiring JSON: ~2M threads from math.SE + MathOverflow (from P7 superpod run)]
    data[Expression surfaces: s-exp parse of every LaTeX expression (from Stage 8)]
    data[NER terms + scopes: from existing pipeline stages 3-5]
    data[Categorical detections: from nlab-ct-reference.json (ships with repo)]
    data[Tag co-occurrence matrix: from SE metadata (free training signal)]
    data[SE "related questions" links: from Posts.xml RelatedPostIds (free training signal)]

  + EVIDENCE:
    evidence[NNexus Glasses demo: all 5 annotation layers rendered for thread #633512 (data/first-proof/nnexus-glasses-demo.html)]
    evidence[Expression surfaces: s-exp parses for ~30 expressions including display math diagrams]
    evidence[Scope maps: structured hx/ends decomposition (Let Γ : directed-graph, ∀ e ∈ E, where U(−) : forgetful-functor)]
    evidence[200-thread pilot: wiring + NER + scopes + categorical for 4 corpora confirms annotation layers are producible at scale]
    evidence[CT discrimination: 81-89% true positive on category-theory threads vs 18-34% on non-CT — the typing works]

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[Build LaTeX → s-exp parser (Python, recursive descent, handle common math constructs)]
    next[Define hypergraph JSON schema for thread structural signatures]
    next[Assemble hypergraphs for 200-thread pilot set (validate schema on real data)]
    next[Survey graph embedding models: Graphormer vs GPS vs HGNN+ for typed hypergraphs]
    next[Build contrastive training dataset from SE tag co-occurrence + related-questions links]
    next[Train prototype on 200-thread pilot, evaluate on held-out tag prediction]
    next[Scale to full math.SE corpus on superpod (GPU stage after P7/P10 pipeline)]
    next[Build FAISS index and structural search demo]

  :success-criteria
    pass[Hypergraph assembly produces valid typed graphs for >95% of threads]
    pass[Embedding model trained on 2M threads converges]
    pass[Structural neighbours share tags at >2x rate of text-embedding neighbours]
    pass[Cross-domain structural matches validated by human review (>60% agreement)]
    pass[FAISS index supports <100ms query time for structural search]
    fail[Embeddings degenerate (all threads map to same region)]
    fail[Structural similarity no better than tag co-occurrence baseline]
    fail[Hypergraph assembly crashes on >5% of threads due to malformed annotations]

  :psr-example "Selected hypergraph embeddings because text embeddings cannot capture argument structure"
  :pur-template "Embedding run {{id}}, threads: {{count}}, model: {{arch}}, tag-pred-accuracy: {{acc}}"
